      ],
      "depth": 1,
      "type_signature": "(ppg: 1-D numeric array representing the photoplethysmography waveform signal, sampling_rate: positive scalar (Hz) \u2014 number of samples per second) -> array or list of integer sample indices marking detected heart-cycle boundaries (e.g. systolic peaks or onset points)",
      "matched_primitive": null,
      "primitive_binding_confidence": 0.0,
      "primitive_binding_source": "",
      "is_optional": false,
      "is_opaque": false,
      "is_external": false,
      "parallelizable": false,
      "conceptual_summary": "periodic_boundary_detector. Scans a uniformly-sampled 1-D scalar time-series to locate the integer indices of recurring structural landmarks that delineate one complete oscillatory cycle from the next. The detector leverages the known temporal density of the signal (samples per unit time) to normalize expected inter-landmark spacing, suppressing aperiodic noise and aliasing artefacts. The result is a sparse index set that partitions the continuous waveform into a sequence of structurally homologous segments.. Applications: Seismology \u2014 detecting recurring P-wave or S-wave onset boundaries in a continuous ground-motion time-series sampled at a fixed rate, segmenting the record into individual seismic events for envelope analysis, Mechanical engineering / condition monitoring \u2014 identifying each rotation cycle of a rotating shaft or bearing from a vibration accelerometer signal, enabling per-revolution feature extraction for fault detection, Neuroscience / electrophysiology \u2014 locating the onset indices of individual oscillatory bursts (e.g., alpha spindles or theta cycles) in a continuously sampled local-field-potential or EEG trace, partitioning the recording into cycle-aligned epochs, Astronomy / photometry \u2014 finding the boundary indices of successive flux oscillation cycles in a stellar light-curve time-series sampled at a known cadence, supporting period estimation and transit timing variation analysis",
      "critic_notes": "",
      "decomposition_rationale": ""
    },
